Adjust the height of a guitar's tremolo system, start by loosening the strings to relieve tension on the system. Then, locate the adjustment screws which are usually at the base of the tremolo or on the bridge. Make small adjustments to the screws, turning them clockwise to lower the tremolo and counterclockwise to raise it, being careful not to overshoot. After making adjustments, test the tremolo by playing a few notes and checking for any buzzing or unwanted sounds. Repeat the process until you are satisfied with the height. Finally, retune the guitar and check for any further adjustments that may need to be made.

About this item    WHAT IS DUAL-LAYER POP FILTER?-Ever seen footage of your favorite artist recording their vocals in a studio? Most likely, you saw a strange black circle standing in between them and the blue yeti microphone.A pop filterÔºåpop shield or pop screen is a circle of nylon mesh that‚Äôs positioned a few inches in front of the mic.It‚Äôs clipped to the mic stand via an 360¬∞adjustable metal gooseneck mount.and the Pop filters can also keep saliva off the condenser microphone.    WHY DO POPING SOUNDS OCCUR?-Generally, plosive sounds are those heard on letters like P, B and S, Imagine singing a phrase like ‚Äúbreak my heart‚Äù into the microphone.It will cause a loud blast of air to head directly towards the microphone‚Äôs capsule, causing it to overload unpleasantly. This causes the microphone to ‚Äúpop‚Äù at that point in the word. just like you are holding a lit candle in front of your mouth while you‚Äôre speaking, these sounds would make the flame flicker.    HOW DOES THE POP FILTER WORK?-Popping sounds can be heightened if you have your mouth too close to the microphone when recording. The plosive sounds interact with the microphone‚Äôs first diaphragm, The gap in between then disperses any remaining air pressure, so by the time it passes the second screen.the blast is easily contained..A mic pop shield or filter acts as a barrier between these sounds and the microphone, with the aim of eliminating them altogether in the final product.
